Also the meltdowns are never meant to “manipulate” they are real actual feelings that aren’t controllable. No one gets that unless you have to deal with it yourself.

It stinks, learning these things at 31, 35, 41, when your life has gone so far and you never understood yourself. Now you do, and you can make your own choices, but you can’t undo the damage from when you were young & didn’t & your life wasn’t always your choice.

But, unlike someone with autism, (at least I think so) complete silence doesn’t help. Because then my racing & hyperactive mind got too loud. Add in anxiety with low self esteem and that gets overwhelming. I would have issues all the time & the adults around me didn’t get it.

When I was a preteen and teenager, I hated the lunch room. It was noisy, smelly, and I was bullied every damn day. By the time I was a senior I was often escaping to the band room as soon as I was done with lunch to a practice room to “practice” something and be alone.

Both threads are interesting to me because I’m not autistic, but I have ADHD which has emotional disregulation & rejection sensitivity and I feel like I sometimes have sensory issues like….sometimes I have so much piled on me that I Just. Can’t. Deal. & I meltdown. 🧵 https://t.co/U3GCpN7Jai

Anyway, I see you fellow Bi people. And I’m letting myself be seen more too.

This means also fighting stereotypes like the “All Bi people should be poly” thing or that Bi people don’t belong at Pride. Pride for the town I live in is actually this weekend. (It’s a college town, so holding it in June doesn’t make as much sense I guess)

I’m trying to embrace it more, so I am trying hard to hide it less. But I still have moments where I want to hide, and I have to remind myself that being visible is important for myself and for those thinking they might be Bi themselves.

I’ve spent most of the last 22 years hiding my sexuality except in small snippets here and there with certain audiences and in private hating the fact that I am Bi and not straight. But it’s still part of who I am, whether I like it or not.

When I met my current husband he was much more supportive of my sexuality, but it’s been hard because I am really more monogamous and it’s been suggested to me enough that I should be poly because I’m Bi that it makes me want to hide it again.

He was very possessive & had anger issues, so I just squashed a lot of how I felt at the time & played straight.

After I left him, I wanted to date a woman, but I was living w/ my parents again & knew they would never approve, so back to hiding my feelings & playing straight.

Shortly after that I ended up involved with and married to my abusive first husband who assured me he didn’t think it was bad that I was bi, but I was only allowed to be turned on by women if he thought there was the possibility of a threesome.

The girl was interested in making out further but the idea made me uncomfortable because she was drunk. I feel I made the right decision in refusing because she was confused like I was but she was also mortified.
I discovered I was Bi in college in 1999. Ended up kissing by a drunk girl on a dare and I had many questions about the feelings that followed.
For #BiVisibilityDay I wanted to express something that’s been hard for me and that’s my own struggle with being Bi (thread)

I learned these things mainly through the competitive events which nearly always had a presentation component. Now I can give demos and speak about my work without much nerves/stress because I have that training. Just some food for thought for tech students in their futures.

I say all that to say this: CS students really should pay attention to speaking/communications classes and I really suggest becoming part of leadership organizations that teach these skills. I was part of #FBLAPBL when I was at Illinois State. It taught me a lot.
Even if you end up working for a larger company, you would still need to present your work to management and if you can speak about your work smoothly and eloquently, it’s very impressive.

Granted I work in UI/UX so for me the framing is a bit different. I am more likely to be called upon to show my work to clients and managers. I’d be willing to bet that the smaller the company you work for, the more you need to multitask. The role of code monkey is rare.

It always strikes as interesting how a lot of CS students don’t really think that presentation and speaking skills are important. Every tech job I’ve had thus far has required such skills and I’ve gotten comments from management how they are impressed by my presentation skills.
